Data Collection and Handling¶

Background¶

Crimes and Economic growth¶

According to the economic theory, crime will generally decrease with the improvement of economic growth and opportunity in a country. Essentially, this argument follows the asumption that the incentive to take part in illegal activities will decrease as legal avenues of earning income become more available and accessible to the public (Street, 2019). However, Street (2019) argues that there are documented cases where economic growth has led to higher crime rates.

To a large extent, Criminal activity acts like a tax on the entire economy of a given country: whether directly or indirectly, crimes tend to discourage both domestic and foreign direct investments, besides affecting the competetiveness of firms, and reallocates resources creating uncertainty and inefficiency (Detotto & Otranto, 2010). Therefore, reduction of crime is among the central objectives of any given authority as a means of attracting entrepreneurial activities, investment, etcetera in a bid to facilitate the generation of employment and subsequently reducing poverty level and improving standards of living. This observation is supported by Teresa (2018) who notes that, "...The necessity for effective crime prevention measures to reduce criminal activity and increase public safety is being recognized as a priority in many countries"

There exists a number of crime-combating strategies some of which include vocational training for older offenders, monitoring by special units for high-risk repeat offenders, arrests, etcetera. However, to fully combat crime it is essential that the dynamics of crime in the area under focus is fully understood. One such method with which to understand the dynamics of crime is through the utilization of data analytics tools (Cavallaro, et al., 2020).

Crime and Data Analytics¶

A simple google for the phrase "crime and data analytics" returns approximately 242,000,000 results which ideally points to the observation of the interest accorded to the two concepts. According to a study by Sri (2021), Modern data analytics uses machine learning to identify patterns and create more accurate criminal profiles in significantly less time, which can then be used to capture criminals. Various approaches have been adopted in the process of utilizing data to understand crime dynamics depending on the underlying aspect i.e., regional analysis of crime or even analyzing a specific type of crime. Data analysis using big data has equally attracted considerable interest. Crimes that have been explored by previous studies using big data technologies including but not limited to data mining and predictive analytics include fraud, smuggling, money laundering, identity theft, and murder etctera.

Matthews (2017) argues that concerning the question of whether big data can be utilized to allow the prevention of crime, big data can enable law enforcement to better prepare and come up with preplanned missions, facilitate the nabbing of criminals at the opportune moment, thus preventing further crimes from taking place. In her article, (Matthews, 2017) observes that one such program was adopted by the Los Angeles Police Department (LAPD) to reduce crime in the Los Angeles metropolitan area, and it worked.

Objective¶

The objective of the current study is to examine the demographic distribution of crimes reported in Southern Australia. In particular, the current study seeks to determine the regions that have the most crimes and those that have relatively few crimes. Besides, the current work will examine the trend exhibited by the number reported crimes in South Australia.

Methods¶

Data¶

To address the current research problem, a secondary data collection approach was adopted where data related to the reported crimes in South Australia was collected. Additional data that provides information on the names of the postal codes included in the crime data was collected. Below is a description of the collected data.

Since the objective of the current study is to examine the behavior of the reported crimes in 2021, the data will be filtered off to include only the information related to the crimes reported in the year of research interest.

Data Description¶

Suburb-based crime statistics for crimes against the person and crimes against property.

Datasets have been enhanced to include sexual assault and related offences in a way that excludes location to ensure confidentiality for victims of those offences.

Crime data was collected from https://data.sa.gov.au/data/datastore/dump/e0b8d120-65e3-44e6-9e2e-aeb7aec59114?bom=True

Post code data was collected from https://www.worldpostalcodes.org/l1/en/au/australia/list/r1/list-of-postcodes-in-south-australia

Exploratory data analysis¶

The objective of the exploratory analysis is to:

  1. Determine the distribution of reported crimes across surburbs, post codes where the incident occurred, the various offence levels.

  2. Examine the distribution of crimes through cross-tabulation on different levels including offence level 1, 2, and 3 descriptions

  3. Examine the change in levels of crime in the 2020-2021

Distribution of crimes¶

Trend of crimes in the year 2020-2021¶

The objective is to establish whether the number of crimes reported in South Australia were increasing throughout the year. To do so, a trend plot will be generate besides using the Mann-Kendall Trend Test to determine whether the observed trend is significant. In practice, the Mann-Kendall Trend Test analyzes difference in signs between previous and subsequent data observations. The theory behind the test is that if a trend exists, the sign values will generally tend to increase constantly, or decrease constantly.

Test to determine whether or not a trend exists in number of reported crimes over time¶

The hypotheses for the test are as follows:

H0 (null hypothesis): There is no trend present in the data.

HA (alternative hypothesis): A trend is present in the data. (This could be a positive or negative trend)

If the p-value of the test is lower than some significance level (common choices are 0.10, 0.05, and 0.01), then there is statistically significant evidence that a trend is present in the time series data.

In [140]:

Mann_Kendall_Test(trend='no trend', h=False, p=0.6954643208013291, z=-0.3914504320878186, Tau=-0.019643953345610803, s=-320.0, var_s=664091.3333333334, slope=-0.0196078431372549, intercept=285.7647058823529)

From the results given above, the p-value is approximately 0.6954 which is not less than .05. As such, we can conclude that there is no significant trend in the number of reported crimes in the year 2021 i.e., the number of crimes tended to remain constant throughout the year.

Conclusion¶

Based on the analyses above, the following conclusions were drawn:

  1. Southern Australia experiences more property crimes relative to person-targeted crimes

  2. Salisbury, Playford, and Port Adeleide Enfield were the most dangerous postcodes in 2021

  3. Adelaide, Morphette, and Port Augusta were the most unsafe surbubs in 2021
  4. Out of the 1031 surburbs which experienced crime in 2021, 460 are comparatively safe given that they had only experienced 5 crimes in the whoe year while 188 are very safe with only a single crime reported. This implies that only 18.23% of South Australia was very safe in 2021
  5. The level of crimes remained constant throughout the year indicating the crimes are not influenced by factors such as seasons.
